{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.4.0"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceId":14711816,"sourceType":"datasetVersion","datasetId":9399494}],"dockerImageVersionId":30749,"isInternetEnabled":false,"language":"r","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/joylorna/smart-device-usage-analysis?scriptVersionId=302796606\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Bellabeat Case Study — SQL Analysis**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Introduction**\n\nThis case study analyzes user activity and sleep behavior using the Bellabeat Smart Devices Health Dataset. The objective is to identify trends in physical activity, sleep duration, and engagement patterns, and to provide actionable recommendations that can help Bellabeat improve user wellness and strengthen product adoption. The analysis bridges technical SQL workflows with business insights, demonstrating how wearable data can inform strategic decision-making.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Methodology**\n\n1. Data Cleaning\n- Timestamp Conversion: Converted string-based timestamps into proper DATE, DATETIME, or TIMESTAMP formats to enable time-based analysis (e.g., extracting hours, weekdays).\n- Error Handling: Identified and corrected schema mismatches and quoting errors during CSV uploads to BigQuery.\n- Deduplication: Removed duplicate records and ensured distinct entries for user IDs and activity logs.\n- Standardization: Normalized column names and formats across tables (daily activity, hourly steps, minute-level sleep) for consistency.\n2. Schema Definition\n- Manual Schema Setup: Defined explicit column types (e.g., INTEGER for steps, FLOAT for calories, DATE for activity_date) to avoid type inference errors.\n- Sleep Data Transformation: Aggregated minute-level sleep logs into daily summaries with calculated fields:\n- total_minutes_asleep\n- total_time_in_bed\n- sleep_efficiency_pct (percentage of time in bed spent asleep).\n- Activity Data Alignment: Ensured consistent keys (id, activity_date) across tables to enable joins between activity and sleep datasets.\n3. Aggregation & Analysis\n- Descriptive Statistics: Computed averages, medians, and distributions for steps, active minutes, sedentary minutes, and sleep duration.\n- Correlation Analysis: Measured relationships between activity and sleep metrics (e.g., steps vs sleep hours, sedentary time vs sleep).\n- Trend Analysis:\n- Grouped activity by day of week to identify weekday vs weekend patterns.\n- Aggregated hourly steps to highlight peak activity times.\n- Bucketed users by active days to assess engagement levels.\n- Visualization: Created histograms, scatter plots, and boxplots in Google Sheets to illustrate distributions and correlations.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**SQL Sample Queries Used in the Methodology Stage**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"SELECT Id, ActivityDate, COUNT(*)\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit.daily_activity`\nGROUP BY Id, ActivityDate\nHAVING COUNT(*) >1;\n\nSELECT *\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit.daily_activity`\nWHERE TotalSteps IS NULL OR Calories IS NULL;\n\nSELECT MAX(TotalSteps) AS max_total_steps, MIN (TotalSteps) AS min_total_steps, MAX(Calories) AS max_calories, MIN(Calories) AS min_calories\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit.daily_activity`;\n\nSELECT COUNT(TotalSteps)\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit.daily_activity`\nWHERE TotalSteps = 0;\n\nCREATE OR REPLACE TABLE `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_activity_cleaned` AS\nSELECT \n  Id AS id,\n  ActivityDate AS activity_date,\n  TotalSteps AS total_steps,\n  TotalDistance AS total_distance,\n  VeryActiveMinutes AS very_active_mins,\n  FairlyActiveMinutes AS fairly_active_mins,\n  LightlyActiveMinutes AS lightly_active_mins,\n  SedentaryMinutes AS sedentary_mins,\n  Calories AS calories\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit.daily_activity`;","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"SELECT id, activityhour, COUNT (*)\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit.hourly_calories`\nGROUP BY id, activityhour\nHAVING COUNT(*) >1;\n\nSELECT *\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit.hourly_calories`\nWHERE calories IS NULL;\n\nSELECT\nid,\nFORMAT_DATETIME('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S', PARSE_DATETIME('%m/%e/%Y %I:%M:%S %p', activityhour)) AS formatted_activity_hour,\ncalories\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit.hourly_calories`;\n\nCREATE OR REPLACE TABLE `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.hourly_calories_cleaned` AS\nSELECT\nid,\nFORMAT_DATETIME('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S', PARSE_DATETIME('%m/%e/%Y %I:%M:%S %p', activityhour)) AS formatted_activity_hour,\ncalories\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit.hourly_calories`;","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Activity Analysis**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"SELECT\n MIN(total_steps) AS min_steps,\n MAX(total_steps) AS max_steps,\nROUND (AVG(total_steps), 0) AS avg_steps,\nAPPROX_QUANTILES(total_steps, 2)[OFFSET(1)] AS median_steps,\n ROUND(100 * COUNTIF(total_steps >= 10000) / COUNT(*), 2) AS percent_meeting_goal\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_activity_cleaned`;\n\nSELECT\n  CASE\n    WHEN total_steps < 5000 THEN 'Sedentary (<5k)'\n    WHEN total_steps >= 5000 AND total_steps < 7500 THEN 'Lightly Active (5k-7.5k)'\n    WHEN total_steps >= 7500 AND total_steps < 10000 THEN 'Fairly Active (7.5k-10k)'\n    WHEN total_steps >= 10000 THEN 'Highly Active (10k+)'\n  END AS activity_category,\nCOUNT(*) AS number_of_days\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_activity_cleaned`\nGROUP BY activity_category\nORDER BY \n  CASE \n   WHEN activity_category = 'Sedentary (<5k)' THEN 1\n   WHEN activity_category = 'Lightly Active (5k-7.5k)' THEN 2\n   WHEN activity_category = 'Fairly Active (7.5k-10k)' THEN 3\n  ELSE 4 \n  END;","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Users were generally less active than recommended health guidelines. Most users fall below optimal activity levels, indicating a large opportunity for behavior-change messaging and motivation-focused features.","metadata":{},"attachments":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Usage Consistency (Device Engagement)**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"SELECT\nid,\nCOUNT (activity_date) AS active_days\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_activity_cleaned`\nGROUP BY id\nORDER BY active_days DESC;","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"User engagement varied significantly.\n* A small group of users wore their devices consistently (30+ active days).\n* The\n majority showed partial or declining usage, with many active for only 8–15 days.\n\nDrop-off behavior suggests that maintaining long-term engagement is a major challenge and a critical area for Bellabeat to address through habit-building features and retention campaigns.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"** Time-of-Day & Weekly Activity Patterns**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"SELECT\n EXTRACT(HOUR FROM PARSE_DATETIME('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S', formatted_activity_hour)) AS hour_of_day,\n ROUND (AVG(steptotal), 2) AS avg_steps\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.hourly_steps_cleaned`\nGROUP BY hour_of_day\nORDER BY avg_steps DESC;","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Users follow predictable routines, making time-based nudges and scheduled notifications an effective marketing and engagement strategy.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Sleep Behavior and Recovery & Relationship Between Activity and Sleep**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"CREATE OR REPLACE TABLE `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_sleep_summary` AS\nSELECT\n  id,\n  log_id,\n  -- We extract the date from the timestamp to know which day this happened\n  DATE(sleep_timestamp) AS sleep_date,\n  -- Each row represents 1 minute. We count only rows where state = 1 (asleep)\n  COUNTIF(sleep_state = 1) AS total_minutes_asleep,\n  -- Total rows for this log_id = total minutes spent in bed\n  COUNT(sleep_state) AS total_time_in_bed,\n  -- Calculate Efficiency: What % of time in bed was actually spent sleeping?\n  ROUND(COUNTIF(sleep_state = 1) / COUNT(sleep_state) * 100, 2) AS sleep_efficiency_pct\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.minute_sleep_cleaned`\nGROUP BY id, log_id, sleep_date;\n\nSELECT\n ROUND (AVG(total_minutes_asleep)/60, 2) AS avg_sleep_hours,\n ROUND (AVG(total_time_in_bed)/60, 2) AS avg_bed_hours,\n ROUND (AVG(sleep_efficiency_pct), 2) AS avg_efficiency\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_sleep_summary`;\n\nSELECT \n  a.id,\n  a.activity_date,\n  a.total_steps,\n  a.very_active_mins,\n  a.sedentary_mins,\n  s.total_minutes_asleep,\n  s.sleep_efficiency_pct\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_activity_cleaned` AS a\nINNER JOIN `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_sleep_summary` AS s\n  -- Casting both IDs to STRING to ensure a perfect match\n  ON CAST(a.id AS STRING) = CAST(s.id AS STRING) \n  AND a.activity_date = s.sleep_date;\n\nSELECT \n  -- Correlation between steps and minutes asleep\n  ROUND(CORR(total_steps, total_minutes_asleep), 2) AS corr_steps_vs_sleep,\n  -- Correlation between active minutes and sleep efficiency\n  ROUND(CORR(very_active_mins, sleep_efficiency_pct), 2) AS corr_active_vs_efficiency,\n  -- Correlation between sedentary time and sleep (usually a strong negative!)\n  ROUND(CORR(sedentary_mins, total_minutes_asleep), 2) AS corr_sedentary_vs_sleep\nFROM (\n  SELECT \n    a.total_steps,\n    a.very_active_mins,\n    a.sedentary_mins,\n    s.total_minutes_asleep,\n    s.sleep_efficiency_pct\n  FROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_activity_cleaned` AS a\n  INNER JOIN `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_sleep_summary` AS s\n    ON CAST(a.id AS STRING) = CAST(s.id AS STRING) \n    AND a.activity_date = s.sleep_date\n);\n\nSELECT \n  FORMAT_DATE('%A', activity_date) AS day_of_week,\n ROUND (AVG(total_steps), 2) AS avg_steps,\n ROUND (AVG(very_active_mins), 2) AS avg_active_mins,\n ROUND (AVG(sedentary_mins), 2) AS avg_sedentary_mins\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_activity_cleaned`\nGROUP BY day_of_week\nORDER BY \n  CASE \n    WHEN day_of_week = 'Monday' THEN 1\n    WHEN day_of_week = 'Tuesday' THEN 2\n    WHEN day_of_week = 'Wednesday' THEN 3\n    WHEN day_of_week = 'Thursday' THEN 4\n    WHEN day_of_week = 'Friday' THEN 5\n    WHEN day_of_week = 'Saturday' THEN 6\n    WHEN day_of_week = 'Sunday' THEN 7\n  END;","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Average Sleep Metrics\n* Average sleep duration: 3.72 hours\n* Average time in bed: 4.03 hours\n* Average sleep efficiency: 91.24%\n\nInsight:\n Although sleep efficiency is high, total sleep duration is well below the recommended 7–9 hours, indicating widespread sleep deprivation among users.\n\nPearson correlation analysis revealed weak relationships:\n* Steps vs. Sleep Duration: -0.11\n* Active Minutes vs. Sleep Efficiency: 0.06\n* Sedentary Minutes vs. Sleep Duration: -0.19\n\nInterpretation\n* More steps did not lead to more sleep\n* High-intensity activity had little effect on sleep efficiency\n* Increased sedentary behavior showed the strongest (negative) relationship with sleep\n\nInsight:\n Sleep quality appears more influenced by sedentary behavior and lifestyle habits than by activity volume alone.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**User Segmentation**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"SELECT\n  CASE\n    WHEN total_steps < 5000 THEN 'Low Activity'\n    WHEN total_steps BETWEEN 5000 AND 9999 THEN 'Moderate Activity'\n    ELSE 'High Activity'\n  END AS activity_level,\n  COUNT(*) AS days\nFROM `project-f57ec015-00f5-4842-84d.fitbit_cleaned.daily_activity_cleaned`\nGROUP BY activity_level;","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Users were grouped into three behavioral segments:\n* Low Activity: 197 days\n* Moderate Activity: 133 days\n* High Activity: 127 days\n\n\nInsight:\nDistinct user types exist, supporting the need for personalized messaging and segmented marketing campaigns.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Conclusions**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This analysis reveals that most smart device users are not meeting recommended activity or sleep guidelines and struggle with long-term engagement. While physical activity alone does not strongly predict better sleep, sedentary behavior shows a meaningful negative relationship with sleep duration.\nFor Bellabeat, these insights highlight a strategic opportunity to:\n* Focus on behavioral consistency\n* Reduce sedentary lifestyles\n* Deliver personalized, time-aware wellness messaging\n* Position products as holistic wellness tools rather than step counters\n\n\nBy aligning marketing strategy with real user behavior, Bellabeat can strengthen customer engagement, improve retention, and reinforce its identity as a data-driven wellness brand.\n","metadata":{}}]}